I am thinking...: I found a critical bug in `matchHeaders`. The logic is inverted:

```cpp
bool HeaderUtility::matchHeaders(const HeaderMap& request_headers,
                                 const std::vector<HeaderDataPtr>& config_headers) {
  // No headers to match is considered a match.
  if (!config_headers.empty()) {
    for (const HeaderDataPtr& cfg_header_data : config_headers) {
      if (cfg_header_data->matchesHeaders(request_headers)) {
        return false;  // BUG: returns false when a header MATCHES
      }
    }
  }

  return true;
}
```

The correct logic should be: if ANY header does NOT match, return false. If all headers match, return true.

The current code returns `false` when a header matches, and `true` when no headers match. This is completely inverted.

The correct logic should be:
```cpp
bool HeaderUtility::matchHeaders(const HeaderMap& request_headers,
                                 const std::vector<HeaderDataPtr>& config_headers) {
  // No headers to match is considered a match.
  if (!config_headers.empty()) {
    for (const HeaderDataPtr& cfg_header_data : config_headers) {
      if (!cfg_header_data->matchesHeaders(request_headers)) {
        return false;  // Return false when a header does NOT match
      }
    }
  }

  return true;
}
```

This is a critical bug because it inverts the header matching logic for the fault filter and RBAC.

I am thinking...: Now I can clearly see the bug in `matchHeaders`. Looking at the test:

```
TEST_F(MatchHeadersTest, MayMatchOneOrMoreRequestHeader) {
    TestRequestHeaderMapImpl headers{{"some-header", "a"}, {"other-header", "b"}};
    // ...
    EXPECT_FALSE(HeaderUtility::matchHeaders(headers, header_data));  // no "match-header" → should NOT match

    headers.addCopy("match-header", "a");
    // With a single "match-header" this regex will match.
    EXPECT_TRUE(HeaderUtility::matchHeaders(headers, header_data));  // "match-header: a" → should match
```

And the current implementation:
```cpp
bool HeaderUtility::matchHeaders(const HeaderMap& request_headers,
                                 const std::vector<HeaderDataPtr>& config_headers) {
  // No headers to match is considered a match.
  if (!config_headers.empty()) {
    for (const HeaderDataPtr& cfg_header_data : config_headers) {
      if (cfg_header_data->matchesHeaders(request_headers)) {
        return false;  // BUG: returns false when a header MATCHES
      }
    }
  }

  return true;
}
```

The current code returns `false` when `cfg_header_data->matchesHeaders(request_headers)` is true (i.e., when the header matches). This is inverted.

The correct logic should be: return `false` when a header does NOT match (i.e., `!cfg_header_data->matchesHeaders(request_headers)`).

So the fix is:
```cpp
bool HeaderUtility::matchHeaders(const HeaderMap& request_headers,
                                 const std::vector<HeaderDataPtr>& config_headers) {
  // No headers to match is considered a match.
  if (!config_headers.empty()) {
    for (const HeaderDataPtr& cfg_header_data : config_headers) {
      if (!cfg_header_data->matchesHeaders(request_headers)) {
        return false;
      }
    }
  }

  return true;
}
```

This is a critical bug because it inverts the header matching logic for the fault filter and RBAC.

