arguments.thought:
I found a critical bug in `matchHeaders`. The logic is inverted:

```cpp
bool HeaderUtility::matchHeaders(const HeaderMap& request_headers,
                                 const std::vector<HeaderDataPtr>& config_headers) {
  // No headers to match is considered a match.
  if (!config_headers.empty()) {
    for (const HeaderDataPtr& cfg_header_data : config_headers) {
      if (cfg_header_data->matchesHeaders(request_headers)) {
        return false;  // BUG: returns false when a header MATCHES
      }
    }
  }

  return true;
}
```

The correct logic should be: if ANY header does NOT match, return false. If all headers match, return true.

The current code returns `false` when a header matches, and `true` when no headers match. This is completely inverted.

The correct logic should be:
```cpp
bool HeaderUtility::matchHeaders(const HeaderMap& request_headers,
                                 const std::vector<HeaderDataPtr>& config_headers) {
  // No headers to match is considered a match.
  if (!config_headers.empty()) {
    for (const HeaderDataPtr& cfg_header_data : config_headers) {
      if (!cfg_header_data->matchesHeaders(request_headers)) {
        return false;  // Return false when a header does NOT match
      }
    }
  }

  return true;
}
```

This is a critical bug because it inverts the header matching logic for the fault filter and RBAC.

